If Phoenix can do on the road what it does at
home, the Mercury might still challenge the elite of the WNBA.
article.headline: Streaks come to an end as Phoenix upsets Houston

images.name: Grubin, Gordana 020711 inline
images.caption: Gordana Grubin of Phoenix drives past the Comets on her way to 12 points.

article.linkText: Struggling Phoenix brings Houston's winning streak to an end
article.story:
PHOENIX (AP) -- If Phoenix can do on the road what it does at home, the Mercury might still challenge the elite of the WNBA. At home, Phoenix (8-10) outshot and outplayed Western Conference-leading Houston (15-4) on Thursday, snapping the Comets' 10-game winning streak with a 58-52 victory. It also ended the Mercury's six-game losing slide, including a just concluded 0-5 road trip. ''I didn't think we could win anymore,'' said Phoenix's Jennifer Gillom, who led the Mercury with 14 points and five rebounds. ''There is nothing like home sweet home,'' echoed Mercury coach Linda Sharp. ''I thought we hit some big shots, but the main thing I was proud of was that we played some team defense tonight.'' The biggest shot was Gordana Grubin's 3-pointer with 40.7 seconds left that broke a 52-52 tie. Houston had scored 10 in a row to close a gap Phoenix made early in the second half. After Grubin's long shot, Tina Thompson missed a 3-point attempt and Phoenix ran downcourt, scoring on Adrain Williams' layup. Sheryl Swoopes, who led Houston with 20 points and eight rebounds, missed another long shot with 10 seconds left, ending any last-second comeback. Houston recovered from an 18-point deficit Tuesday against Seattle to win its franchise-best 10th in a row. ''I thought they played well, and I thought we did for about 18 minutes in the second half,'' said Swoopes, the top vote-getter for the 2002 All-Star Game. ''I didn't think we played very well for 40 minutes and that was the difference in the game.'' Grubin had 12 points, 10 in the second half, and four assists. Houston erased a 10-point deficit in the final five minutes, tying it at 52 on Janeth Arcain's 3-pointer with a minute remaining. Arcain added 11 points and Thompson 10 for Houston, which shot just 36 percent (20-for-56) from the field. The Comets missed eight of their first 10 shots of the second half and were just 31 percent (12-for-39) from the field at that point. ''I don't think we shot the ball real well at all,'' said Swoopes. ''We've kind of been struggling with that the whole season. But usually we're more aggressive on defense, so we're stopping other teams from scoring.'' Houston has the lowest-scoring team in the league at 64 points a game, but is giving up just 58 points a contest. On Thursday, Phoenix made 25 of 55 shots (46 percent) in winning for the first time since June 26. ''I told them before the game if we could hold them under 60 points, we would beat them,'' Sharp said. ''We held them to 52. I thought defensively we did the things we needed to do and we outrebounded them (33-28).'' The Mercury used a 10-point spurt early in the second half to take a nine-point advantage. The Comets had a chance to take sole possession of first place in the Western Conference after Seattle routed the conference-leading Los Angeles Sparks on Thursday night. In the first half, Houston ran off seven consecutive points to offset an early deficit. The Comets missed nine of their first 12 shots in falling behind 22-15. Game notes
With her 3-pointer with 7:16 left in the game, Thompson became the Comets' career scoring leader, passing former Phoenix coach Cynthia Cooper, who had 2,537 points in her career. ... Houston made just 34.5 percent of its shots in the first half (10-29), while Phoenix hit 11 of 25 (44 percent). ... Swoopes missed four of her first five shots and had just six points in the first 20 minutes.
